Gulf the usurer , for his time worse than t 'other .
What 's he comes with him ?
Why , Hoard , that married lately the Widow Medler .
Oh , I cry you mercy , sir .
Now , gentlemen visitants , how does Master Dampit ?
Faith , here he lies e 'en drawing in , sir , good canary as fast
as he can , sir ; a very weak creature , truly , he is almost past
memory .
Fie , Master Dampit ! You lie lazing abed here , and I come to invite
you to my wedding dinner ; up , up , up !
Who 's this ? Master Hoard ? Who hast thou married , in the name
of foolery ?
A rich widow .
A Dutch widow ?
A rich widow ; one Widow Medler .
Medler ? She keeps open house .
She did , I can tell you , in her tother husband 's days ; open house
for all comers ; horse and man was welcome , and room enough for
'em all .
There 's too much for thee , then ; thou may 'st let out some to thy
neighbours .
What , hung alive in chains ? O spectacle ! Bedstaffs of steel ?
O Dampit , Dampit , here 's a just judgment shown upon usury , extortion ,
and trampling villainy !
This is excellent , thief rails upon the thief !
Is this the end of cut-throat usury , brothel , and blasphemy ?
Now may 'st thou see what race a usurer runs .
Why , thou rogue of universality , do not I know thee ? Thy sound
is like the cuckoo , the Welsh ambassador ; thou cowardly slave ,
that offers to fight with a sick man when his weapon 's down !
Rail upon me in my naked bed ? Why , thou great Lucifer 's little
vicar , I am not so weak but I know a knave at first sight . Thou
inconscionable rascal ! Thou that goest upon Middlesex juries ,
and will make haste to give up thy verdict , because thou wilt
not lose thy dinner , are you answered ?
An't were not for shame--
Thou wouldst be hanged then .
Nay , you must exercise patience , Master Gulf , always , in a sick
man 's chamber .
He 'll quarrel with none , I warrant you , but those that are bed-rid .
Let him come , gentlemen , I am armed ; reach my closestool hither .
Here will be a sweet fray anon ; I 'll leave you , gentlemen .
Nay , we 'll along with you . Master Gulf--
Hang him , usuring rascal !
Push , set your strength to his , your wit to his .
Pray , gentlemen , depart ; his hour 's come upon him .
Sleep in my bosom , sleep.
Nay , we have enough of him , i'faith ;
Keep him for the house . Now make your best .
For thrice his wealth I would not have his breast .
A little thing would make me beat him , now he 's asleep.
Mass , then 'twill be a pitiful day when he wakes . I would be
loath to see that day come .
GULF
You overrule me , gentlemen , i'faith .
Nay , uncle , let me prevail with you so much ;
I'faith , go , now he has invited you .
I shall have great joy there when he has borne away the widow .
Why , la , I thought where I should find you presently ; uncle , a'
my troth , 'tis nothing so .
What 's nothing so , sir ? Is not he married to the widow ?
No, by my troth , is he not , uncle .
How ?
Will you have the truth on't ? He is married to a whore , i'faith .
I should laugh at that .
Uncle , let me perish in your favour if you find it not so , and
that 'tis I that have married the honest woman .
Ha ! I 'd walk ten mile a' foot to see that , i'faith .
And see 't you shall , or I 'll never see you again .
A quean , i'faith ? Ha , ha , ha !
Pup , pup , pup , pup ! I like not this wine . Is there never a better
